ateHighLow(numbers); // Assert Assert.Equal(9, high); Assert.Equal(1, low); } [Fact] public void CalculateHighLow_UnorderedArray_ReturnsCorrectHighAndLow() { // Arrange int[] numbers = new int[] { 9, 1, 7, 3, 5 }; // Act var (high, low) = HighLowCalculator.CalculateHighLow(numbers); // Assert Assert.Equal(9, high); Assert.Equal(1, low); } } \`\`\` These tests cover the following scenarios: * Empty array * Null array * Single-element array * Multiple-element array with ordered values * Multiple-element array with unordered values Each test verifies that the \`CalculateHighLow\` method returns the correct high and low values or throws an exception as expected."},{"q":"Explain the code, especially for the high and low calculations. The High and Low calculations are as follows: \`\`\`csharp for (int i = 1; i < numbers.Length; i++) { if (numbers[i] > high) { high = numbers[i]; } else if (numbers[i] < low) { low = numbers[i]; } } \`\`\` This code is contained in a for loop that counts from \`i=1\` instead of the more usual \`i=0\`. This is because the initial values of \`high\` and \`low\` are assigned before the loop from \`numbers[0]\` in: \`\`\`csharp int high = numbers[0]; int low = numbers[0]; \`\`\` In this code: * The value of \`high\` will hold the highest value encountered so far in the iteration. If the current value \`numbers[i]\` is higher than \`high\`, it updates \`high\` with the current value. * The value of \`low\` will hold the lowest value encountered so far in the iteration. If the current value \`numbers[i]\` is lower than \`low\`, it updates \`low\` with the current value. * As the loop iterates through all elements of the array, \`high\` and \`low\` will hold the maximum and minimum values in the array, respectively. This algorithm for finding the high and low values has a time complexity of O(n), where n is the number of elements in the array, because it only requires a single pass through the array. This makes it efficient even for large arrays. U